<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1636,2021]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1636,1661]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Description.</emphasis>
All specimens incomplete; 
<typeStatus box="[661,759,1636,1661]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">holotype</typeStatus>
<quantity box="[767,854,1636,1661]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="6.5">6.5 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[969,1055,1637,1661]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
wide for 19 setigerous segments; 
<typeStatus box="[151,247,1673,1697]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">paratype</typeStatus>
<quantity box="[255,342,1672,1697]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="6.5">6.5 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[455,543,1672,1696]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
wide for 17 setigers; Weddell Sea specimens larger, up to 
<quantity box="[1208,1288,1672,1696]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="17.0">17 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
wide for 52 setigers. Body cylindrical throughout, not depressed anteriorly; thoracic region widest; abdominal setigers 2–3 times longer than thoracic (
<figureCitation box="[599,666,1744,1769]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,249,1544,1566]" captionTargetBox="[172,1422,204,1506]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1523]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. Berkeleyia abyssala n. sp. Holotype (USNM 56500). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, anterior abdominal parapodium (setiger 12), posterior view; C, furcate seta; D, abdominal neuropodial spine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245830/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
A). Color in alcohol: light tan to opaque white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1636,2021]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Prostomium conical, narrowing to pointed tip on anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[975,1056,1780,1805]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,201,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Berkeleyia heroae n. sp. Paratype (USNM 60634). A, anterior end, ventrolateral view; B, abdominal parapodium; C, abdominal neuropodial capillaries and bidentate spines; D, same, different neuropodium, arrow denotes bidentate tip of spine; E, abdominal notopodial furcate setae, arrows denote openings in tips of tynes. — Berkeleyia abyssala (Sta. PS- 67 / 142 - 7). F. anterior end, dorsal view; G, thoracic neuropodial capillaries." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245829/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
F, 3A); without eyespots; nuchal organs on posterolateral margin of prostomium (
<figureCitation box="[725,797,1816,1841]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,201,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Berkeleyia heroae n. sp. Paratype (USNM 60634). A, anterior end, ventrolateral view; B, abdominal parapodium; C, abdominal neuropodial capillaries and bidentate spines; D, same, different neuropodium, arrow denotes bidentate tip of spine; E, abdominal notopodial furcate setae, arrows denote openings in tips of tynes. — Berkeleyia abyssala (Sta. PS- 67 / 142 - 7). F. anterior end, dorsal view; G, thoracic neuropodial capillaries." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245829/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
F). Peristomium achaetous, indistinctly separated from prostomium and setiger 1 (
<figureCitation box="[454,531,1852,1877]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,201,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Berkeleyia heroae n. sp. Paratype (USNM 60634). A, anterior end, ventrolateral view; B, abdominal parapodium; C, abdominal neuropodial capillaries and bidentate spines; D, same, different neuropodium, arrow denotes bidentate tip of spine; E, abdominal notopodial furcate setae, arrows denote openings in tips of tynes. — Berkeleyia abyssala (Sta. PS- 67 / 142 - 7). F. anterior end, dorsal view; G, thoracic neuropodial capillaries." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245829/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
F, 3A). Thorax with 10–11 setigers, all of similar size; digitiform postsetal lobes present from setiger 4 (
<figureCitation box="[409,475,1888,1913]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,249,1544,1566]" captionTargetBox="[172,1422,204,1506]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1523]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. Berkeleyia abyssala n. sp. Holotype (USNM 56500). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, anterior abdominal parapodium (setiger 12), posterior view; C, furcate seta; D, abdominal neuropodial spine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245830/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
A). Abdominal notopodia with long, fingerlike postsetal lobes; neuropodia prolonged, expanded subdistally, with short ventral cirrus (
<figureCitation box="[682,749,1924,1949]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,249,1544,1566]" captionTargetBox="[172,1422,204,1506]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1523]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. Berkeleyia abyssala n. sp. Holotype (USNM 56500). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, anterior abdominal parapodium (setiger 12), posterior view; C, furcate seta; D, abdominal neuropodial spine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245830/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1636,2021]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1437,151,752]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
All thoracic parapodia with crenulated capillaries; capillaries with transverse rows of short barbs (
<figureCitation box="[1330,1400,1960,1985]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,201,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Berkeleyia heroae n. sp. Paratype (USNM 60634). A, anterior end, ventrolateral view; B, abdominal parapodium; C, abdominal neuropodial capillaries and bidentate spines; D, same, different neuropodium, arrow denotes bidentate tip of spine; E, abdominal notopodial furcate setae, arrows denote openings in tips of tynes. — Berkeleyia abyssala (Sta. PS- 67 / 142 - 7). F. anterior end, dorsal view; G, thoracic neuropodial capillaries." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245829/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
G). Abdominal notopodia with long and short crenulated capillaries and 2–3 furcate setae; furcate setae with subequal tynes connected by row of fine needles and thin webbing, shaft with vertical rows of minute barbs (
<figureCitation box="[1331,1401,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,249,1544,1566]" captionTargetBox="[172,1422,204,1506]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1523]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. Berkeleyia abyssala n. sp. Holotype (USNM 56500). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, anterior abdominal parapodium (setiger 12), posterior view; C, furcate seta; D, abdominal neuropodial spine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245830/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
C). Abdominal neuropodia with 2–3 short, smooth spines (
<figureCitation box="[766,831,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,249,1544,1566]" captionTargetBox="[172,1422,204,1506]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1523]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. Berkeleyia abyssala n. sp. Holotype (USNM 56500). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, anterior abdominal parapodium (setiger 12), posterior view; C, furcate seta; D, abdominal neuropodial spine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245830/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
D) and 3–6 long, thin, non-crenulated capillaries (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,201,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Berkeleyia heroae n. sp. Paratype (USNM 60634). A, anterior end, ventrolateral view; B, abdominal parapodium; C, abdominal neuropodial capillaries and bidentate spines; D, same, different neuropodium, arrow denotes bidentate tip of spine; E, abdominal notopodial furcate setae, arrows denote openings in tips of tynes. — Berkeleyia abyssala (Sta. PS- 67 / 142 - 7). F. anterior end, dorsal view; G, thoracic neuropodial capillaries." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245829/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
G).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Branchiae from setiger 9–10 or next-to-last thoracic setiger (
<figureCitation box="[887,965,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,201,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. Berkeleyia heroae n. sp. Paratype (USNM 60634). A, anterior end, ventrolateral view; B, abdominal parapodium; C, abdominal neuropodial capillaries and bidentate spines; D, same, different neuropodium, arrow denotes bidentate tip of spine; E, abdominal notopodial furcate setae, arrows denote openings in tips of tynes. — Berkeleyia abyssala (Sta. PS- 67 / 142 - 7). F. anterior end, dorsal view; G, thoracic neuropodial capillaries." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245829/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
F, 3A); each branchia short, subtriangular (
<figureCitation box="[159,226,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="12.[151,249,1544,1566]" captionTargetBox="[172,1422,204,1506]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1523]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 3. Berkeleyia abyssala n. sp. Holotype (USNM 56500). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, anterior abdominal parapodium (setiger 12), posterior view; C, furcate seta; D, abdominal neuropodial spine." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245830/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,962,332,357]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,752]" box="[199,962,332,357]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,332,357]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet is derived from 
<emphasis box="[652,739,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">abyssus</emphasis>
, Latin for deep sea.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,367,392]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[323,548,368,392]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssala" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[323,548,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Berkeleyia abyssala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[556,620,367,392]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[556,620,367,392]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[635,777,368,392]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="weddellia" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[635,777,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. weddellia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[784,848,367,392]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[784,848,367,392]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(see below), and type-species 
<emphasis box="[1197,1338,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName box="[1197,1334,368,392]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="profunda">B. profunda</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
all from abyssal depths differ from the shallow water 
<taxonomicName box="[676,787,404,428]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="heroae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[676,787,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. heroae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[796,862,404,429]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[796,862,404,429]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in having the abdominal neuropodial spines with entire tips instead of bidentate. 
<taxonomicName box="[523,656,440,464]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssala" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[523,656,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. abyssala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[667,734,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[667,734,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[894,1038,440,464]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="weddellia" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[894,1038,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. weddellia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1049,1116,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1049,1116,439,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1179,1316,440,464]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="profunda">
<emphasis box="[1179,1316,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. profunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having branchiae from posterior thoracic setigers instead of abdominal segments. In 
<taxonomicName box="[1058,1191,476,500]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssala" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1058,1191,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. abyssala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1203,1270,476,501]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1203,1270,476,501]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
branchiae are present from setigers 9–10 whereas they are present from setiger 
<quantity box="[927,989,511,536]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.572" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="in" value="18.0">18 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName box="[1000,1145,512,536]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="weddellia" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1000,1145,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. weddellia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1156,1231,511,536]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1156,1225,511,536]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
,
</emphasis>
not stated in 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="profunda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. profunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but not illustrated before setiger 
<quantity box="[638,696,548,573]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.556" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="in" value="14.0">14 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Hartman" box="[704,888,548,572]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Hartman, O. (1978) Polychaeta from the Weddell Sea Quadrant, Antarctica. Antarctic Research Series, 26 (4), 125 - 223. [42 figures. American Geophysical Union, Washington, D. C.]" type="book chapter" year="1978">Hartman (1978)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[899,1125,548,572]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssala" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[899,1125,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Berkeleyia abyssala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1133,1197,548,573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1133,1197,548,573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
also differs from the other three species in having narrow thoracic segments and elongated abdominal segments; both 
<taxonomicName box="[1237,1366,584,608]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssala" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1237,1366,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. abyssala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1373,1436,583,608]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1373,1436,583,608]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[199,340,620,644]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="weddellia" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[199,340,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. weddellia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[347,411,620,645]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[347,411,620,645]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
have a ventral cirrus on abdominal neuropodia, but this is longer and more conspicuous in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,282,656,680]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssala" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[151,282,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. abyssala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[290,355,655,680]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[290,355,655,680]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
. Abdominal neuropodial spines are similarly pointed in 
<taxonomicName box="[1001,1132,656,680]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abyssala" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1001,1132,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. abyssala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1140,1204,655,680]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1140,1204,655,680]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1263,1404,656,680]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="weddellia" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1263,1404,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. weddellia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, but blunt-tipped in 
<taxonomicName box="[414,546,692,716]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Berkeleyia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="profunda">
<emphasis box="[414,546,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">B. profunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1081,727,752]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,752]" box="[199,1081,727,752]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,727,752]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Distribution.</emphasis>
Antarctic and subantarctic seas, abyssal depths of 
<quantity box="[920,1076,727,752]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6435" metricValueMax="4.176" metricValueMin="3.111" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="m" value="3643.5" valueMax="4176.0" valueMin="3111.0">3111–4176 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
